## system/hardware information tool
    * lspci
        * list devices connecting to PCIe
    * dmesg
    * lsmod
        * module information
    * lsof
        * list all open files including loaded modules
    * lshw
    * hwinfo
    * dmidecode
        * a handy command-line utility for sysadmin to find out hardware information right from the operating system
    * modinfo
        * check driver info
    * inxi

## elf related tool
    * nm
        * list symbols from obj files
    * objdump
        * display information from obj files
    * readelf
        * display information about ELF files
    * ldd
        * print shared obj dependencies
    * file
        * check if a obj file has debug_info or stripped
    * strings
        * print any readable symbols in a obj file

## lib
    * ldd
    * ldconfig
        * search default searching path (/lib, /usr/lib) and the path defined in /etc/ld.so.conf, to find avaliable dynamic linking libraries (in format of lib*.so*), and create the link and cache files that dynamic loading process needs (ld.so).
        * The default cache file is /etc/ld.so.cache
    * lld
    * pkg-config

## binary tool
    * xxd
        * make a hexdump or do the reverse
    * hexdump

## file tool
    * cat
    * tail
        * keep tracing the content of output
    * head
    * cmp
        * compare two files byte by byte

## misc tool
    * w3m
        * command-line based browser

## multi-media tool
    * mpv
        * video player
    * ffmpeg
    * ffprobe
    * ffplayer
        * raw yuv/rgb player
    * yuviewer
        * raw yuv viewer
    * yuv player
        * Windows tool
    * mediainfo
    * gstreamer

## network related tool
    * < web perf tool >
        * siege
            * web perf tool, like ab
        * ab

    * < traffic tool >
        * hping3
        * curl
        * scapy
 
    * < sniffer >
        * ngrep
            * search and filter network packets
        * tcpdump
        * tshark
            * command line wireshark, having more functions than tcpdump and will be helpful to analyze large pcap file
        * tcprewrite
        * tcpreplay
        * hexedit
        * editcap
            * Edit and/or translate the format of capture files

    * < config >
        * ethtool

    * < display >
        * lsof
        * netstat
        * ss
            * display sockets' status
        * mtr
            * replace ping and traceroute
        * iftop
            * see network traffic
        * iptraf
            * see network traffic

## every linux networking tool I know -- Julia Evans
* ss, netstat, lsof, fuser
    * check open port
* tc
* rsync
    * copy only changed files over ssh
* ngrep
* tshark
* tcpflow
    * capture and assemble TCP streams
* mitmproxy
    * spy on SSL connections your programs are making
* p0f
    * idenify OS of hosts connecting to you
* openvpn
* wiregurad
    * a newer vpn
* socat
    * proxy a TCP socket to a unix domain socket
* nftables
    * a new version of iptables
* mtr
    * a better traceroute
* tcptraceroute
    * using tcp packets instead of icmp to tracroute
* ethtool
    * manage physical ethernet connections and networks cards
* iw, iwconfig
    * manage wireless networks settings
* sysctl
    * config linux kernel's network stack

* openssl
    * do literally anything with SSL certifacates
* stunnel
    * make a SSL proxy for an insecure servere
* iptraf, nethogs, iftop, ntop
    * see what's using bandwidth
* ab, nload, iperf
    * benchmarking tools
* python -m SimpleHTTPServer
    * serve files from a directory
* ipcalc
    * easily see what 12.21.2.3/25 means
* nsenter
    * enter a container process's network namespace

### http

* httpie
